: 2$. The numbers $1, 2, 3$ appear in order: the 
smallest leg is $1s$, the hypotenuse is $2s$, and the $$\sqrt{3}$$ 
goes with the middle side.}

content.solution:
The altitude divides the equilateral triangle into two 30-60-90 
triangles. The side of the equilateral triangle becomes the hypotenuse 
of the 30-60-90 triangle, and the altitude is the longer leg.

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.7]
 (A) at (0,0);
 (B) at (4,0);
 (C) at (2,3.464);

 (A) – (B) – (C) – cycle;
 (C) – (2,0);
 (2,0.3) – (2.3,0.3) – (2.3,0);

 at (1,0) {5};
 at (1.8,1.7) {$h$};
 at (3,1.7) {10};
tikzpicture
center

If the hypotenuse is 10, then $2s = 10$, so $s = 5$. The altitude 
(longer leg) is:
\[
h = s\sqrt{3} = 5\sqrt{3} \approx 8.66
\]

If the leg is $s$, then the hypotenuse is $s\sqrt{2} = 8$:
\[
s = \frac{8}{\sqrt{2}} = \frac{8}{\sqrt{2}} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{2}} 
 = \frac{8\sqrt{2}}{2} = 4\sqrt{2}
\]

Each leg is $4\sqrt{2} \approx 5.66$.

The longer leg is $s\sqrt{3} = 15$:
\[
s = \frac{15}{\sqrt{3}} = \frac{15}{\sqrt{3}} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{3}} 
 = \frac{15\sqrt{3}}{3} = 5\sqrt{3}
\]

The shorter leg is $5\sqrt{3}$, and the hypotenuse is $2s = 10\sqrt{3}$.

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.35]
 % Roof structure
 (0,0) – (12,0) – (12,6.93) – cycle;
 (12,0) – (12,6.93);

 % Right angle
 (12,0.5) – (11.5,0.5) – (11.5,0);

 % Labels
 at (6,0) {24 ft};
 at (12,3.5) {$h$};

 % Angle
 (2,0) arc (0:30:2);
 at (2.8,0.6) {$30°$};
tikzpicture
center

This is a 30-60-90 triangle. The horizontal span (24 ft) is the longer 
leg ($s\sqrt{3}$), and the height is the shorter leg ($s$).

\[
s\sqrt{3} = 24 \implies s = \frac{24}{\sqrt{3}} = \frac{24\sqrt{3}}{3} = 8\sqrt{3}
\]

The peak is $8\sqrt{3} \approx 13.86$ feet above the wall.
